{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a4951e29-ff0e-413c-b7d8-bb68f12c4f05","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same* versions already recorded; it fixes corrupted/missing files but doesn't upgrade anything.\n\nSince your SDK moved forward but your workloads didn't, `update` will pull the matching MAUI workload packages for the new SDK.\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, also try:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui --force\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6f348009-aa7f-4ae0-8c9e-32e2d7e696d5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question—I don't need to explore any codebase for this.\n\nLet me answer concisely based on my knowledge of .NET workload management.","outputTokens":242,"requestId":"501A:1E6E:181F542:1ADD851:69FA8FAF"},"id":"69916ebe-b67d-423a-9939-8a27291b64b4","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:47:50.985Z","parentId":"6a5d1a26-c6f0-44d6-bf5f-d1479b68e1f8"}
